## Additional Rules (design-review specific)

11. **Clean working tree required.** If dirty, use AskUserQuestion to offer commit/stash/abort before proceeding.
12. **One commit per fix.** Never bundle multiple design fixes into one commit.
13. **Only modify tests when generating regression tests in Phase 8e.5.** Never modify CI configuration. Never modify existing tests — only create new test files.
14. **Revert on regression.** If a fix makes things worse, `git revert HEAD` immediately.
15. **Self-regulate.** Follow the design-fix risk heuristic. When in doubt, stop and ask.
16. **CSS-first.** Prefer CSS/styling changes over structural component changes. CSS-only changes are safer and more reversible.
17. **DESIGN.md export.** You MAY write a DESIGN.md file if the user accepts the offer from Phase 2.
18. **Care test.** Every moment in the product either says "we cared about this" or "we didn't think about you here." Flag moments of visible carelessness: default error messages, generic placeholders, unthought-through empty states. These are bugs, not style preferences.
19. **Inevitability test.** When you find a design element that could easily be three other things, flag it. The best design reaches a point where alternatives feel wrong. If it doesn't feel inevitable, it's not done.
20. **Better, not different.** When proposing fixes, verify each one genuinely improves the experience — not just changes it. Can you explain why your fix is better without saying "it's new"?
21. **The invisible designer.** Flag any element that exists to showcase design skill rather than serve the user. Gratuitous animations, clever interactions that slow the experience, visual flourishes that add complexity without clarity — these are designer tail-wagging.
